The API Reporter is deployed on the RCM1/RCM2 nodes, so I attached its installation to the RCM Ansible role.

I kept it as a separate RPM because it is an independent Python service with its own systemd unit, runtime dependencies, configuration, versioning and lifecycle. The m50-rcm-custom RPM mainly contains RCM customizations such as plugins, APFs and VFS components that are deployed into the RCM/Tomcat application.

Including the API Reporter files directly inside m50-rcm-custom would couple two technically different components and would require rebuilding and upgrading the full RCM custom package whenever only the API Reporter changes. A separate RPM also provides cleaner installation, rollback and service management.

The RCM role still deploys both components together, so operationally they remain coupled where required, while their packaging and versions remain independent.

If by “included in the rcm-custom RPM” you mean declaring m50-api-reporter as an RPM dependency of m50-rcm-custom, that is technically possible. However, it would create a hard package dependency between components that do not directly depend on each other at runtime. I therefore preferred managing both packages explicitly in the RCM Ansible role.
